g.text: monitoring. In this regard, the environment is likely to contain large numbers of fungal
species with pathogenic potential that are currently nonpathogenic for humans be-
cause they lack the ability to grow at mammalian temperatures. If anything, the direct
and indirect effects of climate changes induced by an exponentially growing human
population as drivers of fungal evolution should be an area of intense research in the
decades to come. Widening of the geographic range of innately thermotolerant
pathogenic fungi and the acquisition of virulence traits in thermotolerant nonpatho-
genic environmental fungi may shape the 21st century as an era of expanding fungal
disease for both the fauna and ﬂora of the planet.
